Every day, we make choices‚Äîhow we spend our time, where we direct our energy, and how we invest our resources. These choices might seem small, but they collectively shape the world we live in. They determine which companies, ideas, and philosophies thrive. That‚Äôs why supporting something with a bad philosophy, even if its product is impressive, is a decision that deserves careful thought.<div><br></div><div>Take Suno, for example. Its product‚Äîa tool that allows anyone to create music‚Äîis undeniably cool. It empowers non-musicians to include music in their projects, opening creative doors for many. But the philosophy behind it‚Äîthat humans don‚Äôt enjoy making music‚Äîfeels anti-human. It dismisses the deeply rewarding and transformative process of learning to create music yourself.</div><div><br></div><div>This got me thinking: If I support a company with such a flawed philosophy, I‚Äôm contributing to the spread of that mindset. Whether through my time, money, or endorsement, I‚Äôm helping their ideas gain traction. Even if I don‚Äôt agree with their philosophy, my support indirectly propagates it, allowing it to flourish.</div><div><br></div><div>This principle extends beyond Suno. Every action we take sends a ripple through the world. If we support philosophies we believe are harmful‚Äîwhether out of convenience, curiosity, or admiration for the product‚Äîwe risk amplifying those ideas and their consequences. And over time, those ideas can become normalized, shaping culture in ways we may regret.</div><div><br></div><div>So what can we do? The key is to align our actions with our values. It‚Äôs about critically evaluating not just what a company offers, but what it stands for. Does it nurture humanity, creativity, and growth? Or does it diminish those qualities in pursuit of convenience or profit?</div><div><br></div><div>By making thoughtful choices, we can ensure we‚Äôre contributing to a world that reflects the values we hold dear. It‚Äôs not always easy‚Äîcool products can tempt us, and we might feel our individual actions don‚Äôt matter. But they do. Every choice adds up.</div><div><br></div><div>In a rapidly evolving world, we have the power to influence what flourishes. Let‚Äôs use that power wisely, supporting philosophies and ideas that uplift humanity, not diminish it.</div>
